<article>
    <h1>POS&#xAD;I&#xAD;TIVE LONG-TERM MAR&#xAD;KET OUT&#xAD;LOOK</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201102/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-02"><time>2020-11-02</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline">&#x2022; Eli Lee is head of in&#xAD;vest&#xAD;ment strat&#xAD;egy, Bank of Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore.</span>
    </section>

    <p>Over the medium to long term, how­ever, we be­lieve the out­look for mar­kets is pos­i­tive.</p>
    <p>While elec­tion un­cer­tain­ties may loom large for now, polls sug­gest that the most likely out­come is a Bi­den win with a Demo­cratic sweep of Con­gress. In this sce­nario, we ex­pect Mr Bi­den’s poli­cies to re­sult in higher growth, mod­er­ately ris­ing in­fla­tion and a weaker US dol­lar. This en­vi­ron­ment is favourable for equities, credit, com­modi­ties and emerg­ing mar­kets.</p>
    <p>Even if we see a con­tested US elec­tion or a grid­locked Con­gress out­come that hurts sen­ti­ment and growth for a pe­riod, it is key to re­mem­ber that the US Fed­eral Re­serve is will­ing and able to em­ploy its tools to bend the arc of the econ­omy towards growth.</p>
    <p>With rates near zero, the Fed­eral Re­serve’s most po­tent weapon is money print­ing. As seen in the af­ter­math of the 2008 great fi­nan­cial cri­sis, this tends to ex­ert up­ward pres­sure on fi­nan­cial as­set prices over time.</p>
    <p>In­vestors should ap­proach pe­ri­ods of volatil­ity ahead as op­por­tu­ni­ties to pru­dently buy sound as­sets with a pa­tient, long-term view.</p>


</article>

